docs.abstract: Senator Ron Johnson, a Republican from Wisconsin, incited widespread outrage when he said recently that he would have been more afraid of the rioters who rampaged the Capitol on Jan. 6 had they been members of Black Lives Matter and antifa.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Ron Johnson, a Republican from Wisconsin, incited widespread outrage when he said recently that he would have been more afraid of the rioters who rampaged the Capitol on Jan. 6 had they been members of Black Lives Matter and antifa.

headline.main: Senator Ron Johnson has spread misinformation on the virus, the election, the Capitol riot, even Greenland’s greenness.

byline.original: By Trip Gabriel and Reid J. Epstein

docs.abstract: Stop minimizing the work of movements.
docs.snippet: Stop minimizing the work of movements.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Black Lives Matter movement has had significant wins in recent months. Municipalities have removed statues of racists, corporations have changed branding that reinforced racial stereotypes, schools have cut ties with police forces and cities have reduced police funding.

headline.main: Don’t Believe the Lie That Voting Is All You Can Do

docs.abstract: This much-anticipated show displays a strength and focus doubly important when art and the humanities seem under attack in Washington.
docs.snippet: This much-anticipated show displays a strength and focus doubly important when art and the humanities seem under attack in Washington.
docs.lead_paragraph: Since moving downtown, the Whitney Museum of American Art has grown up, thanks to a larger, dashing new building, more ambitious exhibitions and new responsibilities brought by rising attendance and membership. No surprise, its biennial has grown up, too. Perhaps less expected: So has the art in it. This show’s strength and focus make it doubly important at a time when art, the humanities and the act of thinking itself seem under attack in Washington.

headline.main: Why the Whitney’s Humanist, Pro-Diversity Biennial Is a Revelation

docs.abstract: Mark Miles, a Black officer with the Maryland-National Capital Park Police, says in a lawsuit that his white supervisor and other officers made hateful comments in a work-related text chain.
docs.snippet: Mark Miles, a Black officer with the Maryland-National Capital Park Police, says in a lawsuit that his white supervisor and other officers made hateful comments in a work-related text chain.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a series of text messages, a white supervisor and other police officers in Montgomery County, Md., talked about preparing for a “race war,” and expressed hope that Black Lives Matter protesters would be killed, according to a federal lawsuit filed this week by a Black colleague.

headline.main: Officers Said They Hoped Black Lives Matter Protesters Would Die, Suit Says

docs.abstract: Has the pandemic brought you closer together with friends? Or moved you farther apart?
docs.snippet: Has the pandemic brought you closer together with friends? Or moved you farther apart?
docs.lead_paragraph: Do you find it difficult to keep up with your friendships in a time of social distancing? Do you find it hard to make new friends in the era of remote schooling, and when people are spending so much time more at home? Has the pandemic brought you closer together, or moved you farther apart, from friends?

headline.main: Are You Having a Tough Time Maintaining Friendships These Days?

docs.abstract: Images of his beating at Selma shocked the nation and led to swift passage of the 1965 Voting Rights Act. He was later called the conscience of the Congress.
docs.snippet: Images of his beating at Selma shocked the nation and led to swift passage of the 1965 Voting Rights Act. He was later called the conscience of the Congress.
docs.lead_paragraph: Representative John Lewis, a son of sharecroppers and an apostle of nonviolence who was bloodied at Selma and across the Jim Crow South in the historic struggle for racial equality, and who then carried a mantle of moral authority into Congress, died on Friday. He was 80.

headline.main: John Lewis, Towering Figure of Civil Rights Era, Dies at 80
headline.print_headline: John Lewis, Civil Rights Icon and Congressman, Dies at 80

docs.abstract: This congressional race in Washington State shows the November elections in microcosm.
docs.snippet: This congressional race in Washington State shows the November elections in microcosm.
docs.lead_paragraph: VANCOUVER, Wash. — In March, five months before he became the Republican nominee in a Washington State congressional race, Joe Kent appeared on a webcast hosted by a Gen-Z white nationalist group called the American Populist Union. Kent, who would soon be endorsed by Donald Trump, was there to explain his disavowal of Nick Fuentes, a smirking 24-year-old far-right influencer whom The New York Times has described as “a prominent white supremacist.”

headline.main: The Midterm Race That Has It All
headline.print_headline: To Understand The Midterms, Meet Joe and Marie

docs.abstract: This HBO documentary goes behind the scenes of the Public Theater’s post-shutdown, modern adaptation of “The Merry Wives of Windsor,” featuring an all-Black cast.
docs.snippet: This HBO documentary goes behind the scenes of the Public Theater’s post-shutdown, modern adaptation of “The Merry Wives of Windsor,” featuring an all-Black cast.
docs.lead_paragraph: Rudy Valdez’s documentary, “Reopening Night,” takes viewers behind the scenes of “Merry Wives,” the Public Theater’s first production after the coronavirus pandemic shut down Broadway and other venues until earlier this year.

headline.main: ‘Reopening Night’ Review: The Show Goes On

docs.abstract: The Amazon was never a “land without men.”
docs.snippet: The Amazon was never a “land without men.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Amid political strife and smoke visible from space, the future of the Amazon has rarely been so hazy. Environmentalists see a vanishing rainforest of global consequence. Indigenous leaders see an ancestral home still being exploited by settlers after 500 years of genocidal violence. Brazil’s president, Jair Bolsonaro, sees valuable acreage wasted by “cave men” and Marxists.
